==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tumultuary
<hw>Tu*mul"tu*a*ry</hw> <pr>(t⟦usl⟧*m⟦ucr⟧l"t⟦usl⟧*⟦asl⟧*r⟦ycr⟧;
135)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>tumultuarius</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>tumultuaire</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Attended by, or
producing, a tumult; disorderly; promiscuous; confused;
tumultuous.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧A <xex>tumultuary</xex> conflict.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Eikon Basilike.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>tumultuary</qex> attack of the Celtic peasantry.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Sudden flight or <qex>tumultuary</qex> skirmish.</q> <rj><qau>De
Quincey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Restless; agitated; unquiet.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Men who live without religion live always in a
<qex>tumultuary</qex> and restless state.</q>
<rj><qau>Atterbury.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tumultuate</ent>⟦br⟧
